<text_segment>III. Methodology: from Classical Models to Graph Neural Networks
In order to understand how Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) are capable of revolutionizing recommendation systems, we compare their performance to two classical methods: memorybased Collaborative Filtering (CF) and Matrix Factorization (MF). We test the three methods on the MovieLens 100k dataset. We seek to highlight in which way leveraging graph structure releases a richer modeling bias, unleashing deeper relational patterns in user-item interactions. A. Problem Formulation: Graph-Based Reframing of Recommendation
The MovieLens 100k dataset contains 100,000 explicit ratings (from 1 to 5) given by 943 users to 1,682 movies [3]. Rather than treating these ratings as isolated entries in a matrix, we reframe the task as a learning problem on a bipartite graph: user nodes on one side, movie nodes on the other, and edges representing observed ratings. This shift of perspective highlights what really matters: the relationships. Each rating is not just a data point, but part of a broader interaction network. Our objective is to predict missing ratings - turning the task into a regression problem that learns from structure. We go beyond pure topology by incorporating initial features. Movie nodes are initialized using both their genres (encoded as one-hot vectors) and title embeddings obtained from a pretrained language model. For user nodes, we rely only on their identifiers, represented as one-hot vectors - no additional metadata was considered for them in this study. Figure 2 visualizes this graph, which forms the structural backbone of our GNN-based model

Fig. 2. Illustration of the bipartite user-item graph. nodes represent users and movies; edges represent observed ratings. B. Baseline 1: Memory-Based Collaborative Filtering (Cf)
Memory-based CF assumes that similar users will rate items similarly. It calculates similarity between users (or items) using metrics like cosine similarity or Pearson correlation. The predicted rating $\hat{r}_{u, i}$ for user $u$ on item $i$ is computed as [1]:
\begin{equation*}
\hat{r}_{u, i}=\frac{\sum_{v \in N_{u}} s(u, v) \cdot r_{v, i}}{\sum_{v \in N_{u}}\verts(u, v)\vert}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
where $s(u, v)$ is the similarity between users $u$ and $v$, and $N_{u}$ is the set of users similar to $u$. Although intuitive and easy to implement, this method struggles with data sparsity and fails to capture deeper interaction structures. C. Baseline 2: Matrix Factorization (Mf)
MF learns latent vectors for users and items. The rating matrix $R$ is approximated as the product of two low-rank matrices [2]:
\begin{equation*}
R \approx P Q^{\top}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
where $P \in \mathbb{R}^{\vertU\vert \times k}$ and $Q \in \mathbb{R}^{\vertI\vert \times k}$. Each user $u$ and item $i$ has a latent vector $p_{u}$ and $q_{i}$, and the predicted rating is:
\begin{equation*}
\hat{r}_{u, i}=p_{u}^{\top} q_{i}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
MF captures more abstract interactions than CF, but it still treats users and items as independent entities in a latent space, limiting its ability to model relational context. D. Graph Neural Networks for Recommendation
GNNs approach the problem differently. Rather than compressing the data into independent vectors, they model users and items as nodes and propagate information via edges through message passing. At layer $l$, the embedding of node $u$ is updated by aggregating information from its neighbors [4]:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
h_{u}^{(l)}=\sigma &amp; \left(W ^ { (l) } \cdot \operatorname { A G G R E G A T E } \left(\left\{h_{v}^{(l-1)}\right.\right.\right. \\
&amp; \left.\left.: v \in \mathcal{N}(u)\} \cup\left\{h_{u}^{(l-1)}\right\}\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
where $W^{(l)}$ is a learnable weight matrix, $\sigma$ is a non-linear activation function, and AGGREGATE can be a mean, sum, or max function. This approach enables GNNs to learn complex, higher-order dependencies that MF and CF typically overlook.</text_segment>

