<text_segment>It results in richer representations that are aware of graph topology and interaction patterns. E. Model Structure: Graphsage with Mlp for Edge Prediction
We represent user-item interactions with a Graph Neural Network with the GraphSAGE architecture [5]. As illustrated in figure 3, the model initially learns user and item node embeddings solely from their ID. They are then updated by two stacked layers of GraphSAGE convolution, which propagate information from each node's local neighborhood. Each node embedding is updated using the GraphSAGE update rule:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
h_{u}^{(l)}=\sigma &amp; \left(W ^ { (l) } \cdot \operatorname { C O N C A T } \left(h_{u}^{(l-1)},\right.\right. \\
&amp; \left.\left.\operatorname{AGGREGATE}\left(\left\{h_{v}^{(l-1)}: v \in \mathcal{N}(u)\right\}\right)\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
where $\mathcal{N}(u)$ denotes the neighbors of node $u, W^{(l)}$ is a learnable weight matrix, and $\sigma$ is a non-linear activation function. The user and item latent representations are then fed through a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) that predicts the interaction score for each user-item pair-equivalent to the rating in our regression setting. The model is end-to-end trained with mean squared error (MSE) loss. This architecture allows the network to learn expressive structure-aware representations while preserving the relational inductive bias of the user-item graph. It also allows for more fine-grained predictions than conventional approaches, owing to the inclusion of neighborhood context under message passing. Fig. 3. Illustration of the bipartite user-item graph. nodes represent users and movies; edges represent observed ratings.</text_segment>

